section.para:
The SpellChecker ships as the optional opennlp-spellcheck extension module (package root opennlp.spellcheck). It is a good fit when you need to:
clean up noisy user input (search queries, form fields, OCR output) before tokenization or classification;
normalize a training or evaluation corpus as part of a preprocessing pipeline;
offer interactive "did you mean" suggestions for a single term.
It is not a grammar checker and it does not require a trained statistical model – correction quality is determined entirely by the supplied frequency dictionary.

			The central abstraction is the SpellChecker interface; its default implementation is
			the SymSpell engine. The interface exposes two ways to correct input:

public interface SpellChecker {

  // Suggestions for a single term, bounded by maxEditDistance.
  List<SuggestItem> lookup(String term, Verbosity verbosity, int maxEditDistance);

  // Convenience overload: Verbosity.TOP and the configured max edit distance.
  List<SuggestItem> lookup(String term);

  // Corrects a whole phrase, repairing word splits and merges.
  List<SuggestItem> lookupCompound(String input, int maxEditDistance);
}

			Each suggestion is an immutable SuggestItem record carrying the corrected term, the
			edit distance to the queried term and the corpus frequency of the suggestion. Its natural ordering
			sorts the best candidate first (ascending edit distance, then descending frequency), so
			get(0) is the top suggestion.

public record SuggestItem(String term, int editDistance, long frequency)
    implements Comparable<SuggestItem> { }

			The Verbosity enum controls how many suggestions a lookup call returns:



TOP – the single best suggestion (cheapest to compute);



CLOSEST – all suggestions sharing the smallest edit distance
						found;



ALL – every suggestion within the requested maximum edit
						distance.

			An engine is created from a SymSpellConfig and populated through
			add (unigrams) and addBigram (bigrams). In practice the engine is built
			from a dictionary or loaded from a model (see ), but
			it can also be filled programmatically:

SymSpellConfig config = SymSpellConfig.builder()
    .maxDictionaryEditDistance(2)   // largest precomputed edit distance (default 2)
    .prefixLength(7)                // leading symbols used for deletes (default 7)
    .countThreshold(1)              // minimum count to index a term (default 1)
    .editDistance(DamerauOSADistance.INSTANCE) // verification metric (default)
    .build();

SymSpell symSpell = new SymSpell(config);   // or: new SymSpell() for the defaults
symSpell.add("quick", 1_000);
symSpell.add("brown", 800);
symSpell.addBigram("quick", "brown", 120);

			Once populated, the engine is safe for concurrent lookup calls. Looking up a single
			term and reading the best suggestion:

List<SuggestItem> suggestions = symSpell.lookup("qick", Verbosity.CLOSEST, 2);
for (SuggestItem item : suggestions) {
  System.out.printf("%s (distance=%d, frequency=%d)%n",
      item.term(), item.editDistance(), item.frequency());
}

			Correcting a whole phrase, including wrongly split or merged words, with
			lookupCompound (which always returns a singleton list holding the best correction):

String corrected = symSpell.lookupCompound("thequick brwn fox", 2).get(0).term();
// -> "the quick brown fox"

			A model is the built engine together with its source dictionaries and the metadata needed to
			identify it. The SymSpellModels facade builds, serializes and deserializes models, and
			writes the packaged form consumed by the model-resolver. The loaded model exposes a ready-to-query
			engine via getSymSpell():

InputStreamFactory unigrams = new MarkableFileInputStreamFactory(new File("en-unigrams.txt"));
InputStreamFactory bigrams = new MarkableFileInputStreamFactory(new File("en-bigrams.txt"));

SymSpellModel model = SymSpellModels.buildModel(
    "en", SymSpellConfig.defaultConfig(), StandardCharsets.UTF_8, unigrams, bigrams);

// Persist the binary model.
try (OutputStream out = Files.newOutputStream(Path.of("en-spellcheck.bin"))) {
  SymSpellModels.serialize(model, out);
}

// Reload it later and query the engine.
try (InputStream in = Files.newInputStream(Path.of("en-spellcheck.bin"))) {
  SymSpellModel loaded = SymSpellModels.deserialize(in);
  SpellChecker checker = loaded.getSymSpell();
  List<SuggestItem> suggestions = checker.lookup("qick");
}

			Loading just the dictionaries into an existing engine – for example to add domain terms –
			can be done directly with the loader:

SymSpell engine = new SymSpell(SymSpellConfig.defaultConfig());
FrequencyDictionaryLoader loader = new FrequencyDictionaryLoader(StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
loader.loadUnigrams(engine, unigrams);
loader.loadBigrams(engine, bigrams);

SpellCheckingCharSequenceNormalizer implements opennlp.tools.util.normalizer.CharSequenceNormalizer and can be composed with the other normalizers (URL, emoji, shrink, ...) inside an AggregateCharSequenceNormalizer. It works in one of two modes: Mode.PER_TOKEN (the default) corrects each whitespace-delimited token independently and preserves the line's whitespace and punctuation, while Mode.COMPOUND corrects the whole input as a phrase, repairing word splits and merges. It guards against over-correction (skipping short tokens, numbers and URL/email-like tokens, and never changing a word the dictionary already contains) and preserves the original casing pattern of each token.
SymSpellModel model = SymSpellModels.deserialize(in);
CharSequenceNormalizer normalizer = SpellCheckingCharSequenceNormalizer.builder(model) .mode(SpellCheckingCharSequenceNormalizer.Mode.PER_TOKEN) .maxEditDistance(2) .build();
CharSequence clean = normalizer.normalize("the qick brwn fox"); // -> "the quick brown fox"

			For stream-based preprocessing two FilterObjectStream<String, String>
			implementations wrap an existing ObjectStream<String> and correct each element as
			it is read:




						SpellCorrectingObjectStream corrects each line; in compound mode it may split
						or merge tokens. Use it for free text.





						SpellCorrectingTokenStream corrects tokenized data token-by-token and re-joins
						with the same delimiter. It is token-count preserving, so the corrected
						element stays aligned with any parallel annotation (tags, spans).



			Dropping the corrector into a line-based reading chain:

ObjectStream<String> lines =
    new PlainTextByLineStream(inputStreamFactory, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
ObjectStream<String> corrected = new SpellCorrectingObjectStream(lines, model);

String line;
while ((line = corrected.read()) != null) {
  // ... consume corrected lines ...
}
